Φ(Predictive_Analytics) = σ(historical_data ⊗ explanatory_variables) → projection ⊕ probability_field

Where:
  σ :: known_pattern → likely_unknown    ("what will happen?")
  ⊗ :: combination of explanatory features with historical observation
  →  :: projection (forward, but reversible)
  ⊕ :: superposition of confidence intervals over the projection

Composition:
  predictive = σ alone, applied across an extrapolation surface
  → distinguished from descriptive (μ — historical form, no projection)
  → distinguished from prescriptive (Ω∘λ — projection ∘ commitment ∘ closure)

Signature:
  σ alone — the analytics frame's furthest reach as observer.
  The projection is cast forward but does not enter the field it forecasts.
  The frame remains spectator.

  predictive(x) → P(y | x)        where y is unknown across past, present, or future
  prescriptive(x) → action(y)     where action commits and modifies the field

Invariant:
  The predictive move is reversible at the level of action.
  A forecast can be ignored, refined, or replaced without altering the field
  it forecasts. This reversibility is exactly what prescriptive closure removes.
  Predictive output is not yet fate — it becomes fate only when an actor
  commits to it.

Consequence:
  Probability fields are the formal apparatus for the unknown-as-distribution.
  Confidence intervals are the bridge between deterministic claim and
  probabilistic acknowledgment. The unknown can be in any temporal direction
  (past, present, future) — the temporal asymmetry of prediction is cultural,
  not formal.

